`IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory by default. For large files, read the raw request body stream directly and write to disk in chunks:

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~28 MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024); // 2 GB

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable request buffering so the body is a forward-only stream
    request.EnableBuffering(bufferThreshold: 1024 * 64);

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing multipart boundary");

    var reader = new Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities.MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers.ContentDispositionHeaderValue
                .TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var disposition)
            || !disposition.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue;
        }

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        // Stream directly to disk — only a small buffer is in memory at a time
        await using var fileStream = new FileStream(
            savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write, FileShare.None,
            bufferSize: 81920, useAsync: true);

        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
});

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| Memory buffering | `MultipartReader` reads section-by-section from the network stream — never loads the full file |
| Kestrel body limit | Set `MaxRequestBodySize` to 2 GB (or `null` for unlimited) |
| `[DisableRequestSizeLimit]` | For minimal APIs, use the Kestrel option above or `.DisableAntiforgery()` per-endpoint |
| Form value limit | Not hit — you're bypassing model binding entirely |
| Reverse proxy (nginx/IIS) | Also raise `client_max_body_size` / `maxAllowedContentLength` there |

**Don't forget** to add `DisableFormValueModelBinding` if you also have MVC controllers, to prevent the framework from pre-reading the body:

```csharp
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Method)]
public class DisableFormValueModelBindingAttribute : Attribute, IResourceFilter
{
    public void OnResourceExecuting(ResourceExecutingContext context)
    {
        var factories = context.ValueProviderFactories;
        factories.RemoveType<FormValueProviderFactory>();
        factories.RemoveType<FormFileValueProviderFactory>();
        factories.RemoveType<JQueryFormValueProviderFactory>();
    }
    public void OnResourceExecuted(ResourceExecutedContext context) { }
}
```

This pattern keeps memory usage constant (~80 KB buffer) regardless of upload size.
